{Drury lets a passed hand check whether partner's third-seat opening is sound before committing to game. The whole question on this deal is how high to rest.

[BID 1H] @S @v(open|opens) 1\H in third seat. Because partner has already passed, this opening may be lighter than a first-seat one, so the raise to follow will tread carefully.

[BID 2C] Instead of leaping to game, @S @v(bid|bids) 2\C, artificial Drury. It announces a good heart raise — about ten support points and at least three trumps — and asks partner to confirm the opening is real before the partnership climbs too high.

[BID 2D] @S @v(rebid|rebids) 2\D, the artificial minimum. It says the opening was a sub-fifteen hand with nothing to spare, the warning signal Drury is built to catch.

[BID 2H] With only a minimum raise opposite that minimum opening, game is too high, so @S @v(sign|signs) off in 2\H. Both hands are limited, and settling for a heart partscore keeps the auction safe.

[BID 3H] @S @v(nudge|nudges) once to 3\H, a mild competitive push on the minimum. Responder has nothing more to add and passes.

[show NS] South's ten support points and three trumps were exactly enough for Drury, not for game. Once opener showed a minimum with 2\D, signing off was right: nine tricks are the limit here, and 4\H needs ten and would have gone down. Drury kept the partnership out of a losing game.}
